<div id="review_204063553" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/204063553" />
    <a title="Samuel García" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5963613-samuel-garc-a"><img alt="Samuel García" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442601229p2/5963613.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/204063553?book_show_action=true">Aug 31, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Samuel García" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Samuel García" href="/user/show/5963613-samuel-garc-a">Samuel García</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer204063553" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer807547297472628786">A classic trilogy. &quot;Interview with the Vampire&quot; is its own beast, while the other two go hand to hand as Lestat&apos;s answer to Louis&apos; chronicle. While &quot;Interview with the Vampire&quot; is the better known of all the Vampire Chronicles, and the story is very good, Louis&apos; bleak and whiny vision of the world drags down the reading experience. Lestat, on the other hand, enhances his own story, making it a very fun read. Best of the three would be the last one, &quot;The Queen of the Damned&quot;, but you do need to r</span>
  <span id="freeText807547297472628786" style="display:none">A classic trilogy. "Interview with the Vampire" is its own beast, while the other two go hand to hand as Lestat's answer to Louis' chronicle. While "Interview with the Vampire" is the better known of all the Vampire Chronicles, and the story is very good, Louis' bleak and whiny vision of the world drags down the reading experience. Lestat, on the other hand, enhances his own story, making it a very fun read. Best of the three would be the last one, "The Queen of the Damned", but you do need to read the other two to really enjoy it, else you will be lost.</span>
  <a data-text-id="807547297472628786" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
